improve_survey_comment: would be nice to have access to previous years' information, if possible. would be best to include this question at the end of the survey so i can be fully informed. would be good to have feely questions about people's emotional relationship to the movement and things that have made them feel proud or disappointed in the movement. this is really good feedback as a thermometer on movement growth and tactics that will build and sustain the movement.
ea_welcoming_comment: different spaces have different levels of welcoming-ness. some local groups are very welcoming, some not. some groups are very open to pluralism and diversity, some are very monolithic and normative. the online community is generally very unwelcoming.
insecurity_comment: i'm pretty ea in one narrow sense (hedonistic act utilitarian, presently donating 33% of my income), but many ea spaces aren't very friendly to left politics. which is sad, because these movements could stand to learn a lot from one another and be great natural allies. i recognize the complexities here, but i stand by this claim.

is_ea_comment: Your questions are too wordy. It's impossible to remember the question if there are four lines of commentary after it. The fact that you even ask if people are giving genuine sincere answers is enough to make any normal person run and hide. IF they get past all your freakishly technical and verbose commentary. This in a nutshell shows the insane lack of accessibility of EA to people who don't care about technicalities and people who feel offended when you essentially suggest they might be lying on the very first page of a survey. If you have to make a question like that, put it at the end. And stop writing like someone who's proud they know the word "presumptuous" and making half your words redundant. if you're sincere, you're genuine. And vice versa. If a question is mandatory, then it probably means something won't count. Good lord.

first_heard_ea_comment: EA desperately needs a new brand. I think EA likes the selectiveness that their high falutin nomenclature commands. It weeds out stupid people and it keeps things academic. If you were serious about an EA movement, you would make things more accessible by making all of the concepts you discuss easier to understand in more places. Most people in America probably don't know what Altruism means. And most people in EA probably aren't totally altruistic anyway.
involved_other: Data, Logic. The actual people in EA make me want to never be associated with it ever, but I can't not say I'm an EA because the general philosophy is fine.
attend_local_group_comment: Maybe if I knew what local EA groups did or would do. Attend makes it sound like it's going to church. I would probably prefer something closer to "participate".
veg: Eat meat, but try to reduce the amount I eat
improve_survey_comment: This survey needs to be evaluated by a non-EA impartial judge to remove biases in question framing and inaccessibility issues. I would not trust the results from a large number of the questions.
ea_welcoming_comment: I hate the EA community. There are so many weird relationships between EA members and everyone in the group is so extreme about so many things that I can't handle the amount of opinions. I think a lot of fear exists in the community that people won't admit. Let's hope this person doesn't find out I'm not vegan. Let's hope that person doesn't realize I'm actually a meat eater. Let's hope that person doesn't hate me for believing in God. It's not a very inclusive space, and people seem to like arguing and debating more than collaborating. The movement seems to view itself as an insular community rather than an actual movement trying to invite the outside world.
insecurity_comment: EA has to drop its personality cult to become a widespread philosophy.

ea_org_comment: I've been pretty shocked recently at the groupthink and opposition to critical perspectives in some EA circles. This surfaced most clearly in discussion of Harrison Nathan's critical Medium post about Animal Charity Evaluators, which struck me as an incisive but not ad hominem attempt to scrutinize and dissent against things that EAs often perceive as obvious with little evidence. first_heard_ea_comment:
I was hanging out on Felicifia and corresponding with Toby Ord before the EA movement came into existence. I joined GWWC before the phrase "effective altruism" had been invented. I watched the movement coming into existence.

My interest in the ideas underlying the EA movement dates back to about 1994.

action_fundraiser: I do not intend to do this
ea_org_comment:
I'm conflicted in my views about whether existential risk is the top priority and may move towards giving more weight to this cause in the future. 

I've encountered one article making strong criticisms of Animal Charity Evaluators saying that their work lacks scientific rigour and has sometimes been influenced by inappropriate conflicts of interest, and this is of concern to me and I will attach a lot of importance to investigating this matter further. This is the article: https://medium.com/@harrisonnathan/the-actual-number-is-almost-surely-higher-92c908f36517

I think Animal Charity Evaluators has done a good job of prioritizing areas of research investigation but I would like to see them investigate whether the harm caused by animal experiments is a tractable problem.

I would be very interested to hear about any charity that has a good chance of making progress with improving our level of understanding of the wild-animal-suffering problem.

I welcome the recent news of progress with the development of in-vitro meat.

Although I am uncertain about whether global poverty is the most important cause area I think it is a good one to focus on for outreach purposes.

I appreciate GiveWell's work a lot and probably ought to consider donating to them. I'd like to get a clearer understanding of how one can measure the impact of global-poverty interventions that prevent harms other than premature death. This would be mainly a matter of reading through the research that has already been done on the subject.

ea_org_comment:
Diversity is important! All EA orgs must work harder to include diverse leadership, though not at the expense of the work we are trying to do. 

Intersectionality must be respected among causes. When ACE recommends MFA as a top charity, it does so because MFA is very good at 'saving' animals. But when it does so through undercover investigations, immigrant workers are directly harmed as a result. We need to take into account these outside costs when evaluating the effectiveness of charities.

Other examples of why intersectionality is important include: the need to stay away from body shaming when promoting veganism; the need to stay away from lying in general when promoting EA causes; and the need to not intentionally slow down the economy in order to delay the arrival of AI.

ea_org_comment: Small suggestion: focus on cognitive biases tends to coast over implicit biases based on race and gender. I understand why, since these are highly political topics and conversations on them can be fraught, but there is a lot of evidence that they affect many of our judgements, so I think it's important that we discuss strategies and approaches with these biases in mind. I think they could be quite important e.g. since a lot of EAs are white people from high-income countries trying to help non-white people in low-income countries, so understanding how our judgements are effected by racial bias could have a big impact.

improve_survey_comment: I've noticed that Animal Equality was missing in your list of effective charities although I'm pretty sure it was one of ACE's top charities in 2016. Except for that, I'm very impressed by this survey! One idea I'd like to share: maybe ask an additional question about what people might need from the EA movement or what they don't like about it right now
ea_welcoming_comment:
When I meet EAs in person or when it's about something personal, they're the most welcoming people in the world :) but I'm worried about how welcoming we are towards people who are less privileged or have a different background than many EAs. I've noticed borderline racist and sexist opinions in some EA groups and I get the feeling that discrimination and intersectionality are not taken seriously enough because they're not "rational" or scientifically provable enough.
Another concern I have is that the voices of EA on the internet sound pretty much alike and all very thorough, very scientific and very rational. It has been intimidating me and at least one other person (also female) from my local EA group. We both felt that this way of communicating is very helpful for the goals of EA but that it can also be a hurdle for people new to EA, especially when they don't have a scientific background

ea_org_comment:
I don't think Animal Charity Evaluators dealt with the Harrison Nathan Medium article and resulting fallout well. I'm still quite sympathetic to them and their work, but one of the defenses offered by them/their supporters was that the points brought up by him were already known. The fact that they already knew about issues and hadn't worked on them is not a positive point for them. I can't remember the details very well right now, but I believe something on their website had been outdated for years, people had complained about it privately (I think Elizabeth Von Nostrand said on Facebook she had), they didn't update it, Harrison Nathan criticized it, and they still took quite some time to adequately update it. 

Issues with their research being misinterpreted are also problems that they have responsibility for. I didn't realize how little hard evidence there was for parts of their research until the Nathan article. I was not alone in this. That is a failure of communication on their part.

MIRI is an Eliezer Yudkowsky fan club, not a charity.

first_heard_ea_comment: Oddly enough the thing that first led me to EA was a Louis C.K. routine I saw on Netflix. He has a bit where he talks about how if he wanted, he could save children's lives by trading in his car for a cheaper one and donating the difference - but he doesn't, and this basically amounts to 'killing them every day with his car'. It stuck with me, and a while later I started Googling around to read people's thoughts on it. I found Singer's drowning child argument, and Scott Alexander's post about measuring the cost of things in lives that could have been saved, and from there went on to start following EA blogs, Givewell recommendations, etc.
ea_career_comment: I had no idea what I wanted to do after school, so based off reading 80000 Hours I tried to go into finance. I didn't take to it at all, so for primarily non-EA reasons I switched to medicine. It might not be the most effective choice but I feel much more motivated to work now that I enjoy what I'm doing - so maybe it'll put me in a stronger position re. ETG down the line

Giving What We Can:

I'm extremely troubled by the ambiguity over the permanence of the GWWC pledge. I think the sentiment is "If everything goes roughly as I plan, I will continue to give 10%", but this isn't reflected in the wording. ea_org_comment:
Overall i think the best message coming out of EA is how cheap it is to help people in extreme poverty, and to try and raise a culture of giving. I think to do the most good, these ideals should spread into the culture at large, instead of being insulated in little "nerd" communities, and give maximum leverage in persuading the super-rich to give up their wealth (out of shame). 

Please please please stay away from the AI risk people. the whole point of this movement was meant to be being evidence based, and their whole shtick is completely speculative based on technology that we have no idea about. It will also confine the community to bay area computer types and completely stunt it's growth.

ea_org_comment:
Let's see: the most important matter right now is to make honesty mean something within EA, and to institute social punishment/shame against those who act dishonestly with no plausible deniability. Private feedback should be always given first when people without a history of acting dishonestly do something that's a bit off, but something should be said publicly if they don't change their actions and act with more integrity after receiving feedback and being given several weeks to act on it. Getting rid of the tax on criticism in situations where the criticized parties have already had ample time to respond would have let us deal with Gleb on a much shorter time-scale, and with much less attentional opportunity cost.

I'm happy that some EAs are working on animal welfare. ACE has no place within EA whatsoever, given the way in which they failed to update their website for so long in a way that simultaneously benefited them, was costly to any donors who might have felt misinformed, and was extremely costly to those who had to choose between policing their decision to do this and letting it slide/taking a break. To anyone who hasn't had to police the actions of bad actors after they've been given a warning, let me tell you that this is an *incredibly emotionally costly* thing to do!

I'm dedicated to having the largest positive expected impact that I can, and I'm starting to edge away from EA on account of the lack of integrity and tax on criticism that seem to be settling in as defaults in certain parts of EA. I'll stick around if that changes, since I can't do good things effectively in the current environment.

improve_survey_comment:
Consider and correct for sampling bias more. My intuition here (you can check with your results to see if this is true) is that the people with the highest inclination to get involved (especially those who have the time to look around online) will be overrepresented because it take mental effort to go through these fields (do you know how many people click next at least once but then don't submit?). 

Points on improving user experience
1) The UI here looks out-dated (though I get that it might be useful to code with). The checkboxes/radio-buttons are too small. 
- Typeform would be a smoother experience

2) Some descriptions are unclear or unnecessarily long.
- I took the last EA survey in 2016 so saying 2015 is confusing to me

- "If you have opted in or out of sharing the following information on your EA Profile, please skip this question.  The following information can be shared on your EA Profile.  If you already have an EA Profile or have selected to create one, please check the following categories that you would like to share (check all that apply):" 
–> this is a mess

3) I think you have too many fields that don't add enough value (especially redundant ones for info I've filled in in the past). 

4) This is also my feedback for .impact/Rethinking charity in general. Because projects are initiatives/collaboratives by volunteers there often doesn't seem to be enough focus/direction and too many distractions. I think leaders can add a lot of value by discussing, setting and reinforcing the pursuit of clear objectives.

Having said all this: the extensive data coming out of this survey looks really useful!

ea_org_comment:
Anecdotally, people I have spoken to about EA fall into two camps. On the one hand, some people are basically uninterested. On the other hand, people are almost immediately enthusiastic about the idea, as if it intuitively makes sense and expresses something they were already thinking on some level.

This probably means that 'mass marketing' of the concept as opposed to spending a lot of time trying to persuade individuals is likely to be an optimal recruitment strategy.

ea_org_comment:
The argument of the most effective reduction of poverty and data driven analysis is the strongest tool of the EA movement. It should be the main focus of our work to elaborate on these topics and it underlying implications for personal choice of carreer (like 80000hours does it).

What seems to be missing is a philosophical foundation for the EA movement besides that we all agree on the worth of altruism & human rights. Why we should promote this values is often not discussed or mentioned, as it is viewed as a basic consensus of the community.
Allan Gewirths "Community of rights" provides such an theoretical framework for the EA Movement: He elaborates why mutal assistance & the acceptance and promotion of human rights is not only a moral obligation but a dialectic necessarity that we all as rational agents must give credit to. Discussing his ideas could be a time spent worthy and they are applicable to all sentinent beings too.

However, the discussion of possible future treats could pose a toxic danger to the public work of the community. By engaging in topics that require detailed knowledge we reduce our audience significantly. It is a necessary topic of course, but it should not be in our main focus as a network of activists.

This survey has decreased my desire to cooperate with EA, because it illustrates the extent to which EA sees people as resources to pump with various techniques. The attitude that people should turn over the bulk of their surplus resources and to not do so is blameworthy, shines through every page. This attitude must stop. This is a very bad thing to be doing. One who does so is not virtuous. It is a habit which, when repeated, turns you into bad actors, and it shows others that you cannot be trusted as a group. It is bad for the people you are attempting to manipulate and money-pump, and long term you may destroy their well-being this way, and also decrease their willingness to give or cooperate.  

A lot of those reading these responses are not guilty of such actions, but many of you very much are. Beware, for the sake of everyone! The reason EA exists, and has the ability to do so much good, is because EA has shown itself as dedicated to doing good. But if you are not committed to actually being good in your interactions and dealings, and treating people right, that most valuable asset will be lost, on both levels - you will no longer be doing good, nor will people see you as doing good! Heal and save thyself first.

ea_org_comment:
By rights we shouldn't even be here.
But we are.
It's like in the great stories Mr. Frodo.
The ones that really mattered.
Full of darkness and danger they were,
and sometimes you didn't want to know the end.
Because how could the end be happy.
How could the world go back to the way it was when so much bad happened.
But in the end, it's only a passing thing, this shadow.
Even darkness must pass.
A new day will come.
And when the sun shines it will shine out the clearer.
Those were the stories that stayed with you.
That meant something.
Even if you were too small to understand why.
But I think, Mr. Frodo, I do understand.
I know now.
Folk in those stories had lots of chances of turning back only they didn’t.
Because they were holding on to something.

What are we holding on to, Sam?

That there’s some good in this world, Mr. Frodo. And it’s worth fighting for.

ea_org_comment: I'm just starting out my career. Before I start donating, I want to decide where my donations can do the most good. I'm currently torn between AI research and global disease-fighting (e.g. GiveWell's top picks of the year, malaria etc.). These are wildly different causes and their impacts are difficult to compare. AI risk is especially difficult to quantify for me. Once I've settled on an option, I will probably change it as new evidence comes in, but I will be satisfied enough to begin funneling money in one direction or the other. AI research has a slight advantage at the moment, in my mind, but this is possibly due to my own desire to feel like what I'm doing will be permanent.

> The EA Forum or Facebook group
I hate that so much of EA communication happens on Facebook. I'd rather not use Facebook at all (practical privacy concerns and boycott because of privacy concerns).

> 80,000 Hours
One of the most interesting EA organisations, but the website can be difficult to navigate. It can be hard to find stuff I've seen earlier (like the short career path test).


> Animal Charity Evaluators
Please pay more attention to COI and consider the possible issue of cooptation. Maybe split recommendations based on values (welfare improvement vs. 'abolitionism' if you will).

> Other
Please tell Peter Singer to pay more attention to his public image.

improve_survey_comment: Please ask about birth sex as well as gender. When worrying about how to get more women into the community, the fact that the community seems to be attracting trans women at above-average rates is a relevant and important consideration. Our gender balance problem is not with gender, it is with sex. In addition, I am uncomfortable ticking a box that says I do or do not identify with a certain gender, since I do not particularly want to have to search my soul for an identity-feeling to confess on a survey. I would be much more comfortable answering a simple question about my sex.

ea_org_comment:
To me the important thing in EA is that people decide, either through donations or careers or whatever, to use a reasonable proportion of their good fortune in life to help others (all broadly defined). I'm just a guy with a normally-paid job in a rich country, and I get to save a bunch of people's lives while hardly noticing the difference in my bank account, which is ****** amazing! 

This is probably silly, but I kind of wish the `have a normal job, and donate 10%' approach to EA was emphasised a bit more. I feel that the number of people who can be reached in this way is likely vastly higher than those prepared to e.g. choose their whole career based on EA. Even if the impact per person is less, the number of people who are realistically likely to do it seems so much greater. 

I fear that the message of EA may be getting a little too complicated. You have such a strong basic selling point: if you're a random person in a rich country with a job, and you donate X%, you can save Y lives. This is a message that is really hard to ignore/argue about. Once people are on-board they may get into more esoteric causes (AI, animal rights, etc) and more substantial actions (e.g. career change). But it seems to me that these are not the right approach for attracting large numbers of people.

insecurity_comment:
I am leading a fairly successful EA group turning into an EA org, have interacted a lot with EAs, however, online and I do not feel comfortable interacting with the most hardcore EAs because I feel like I lack credibility.

This is incredibly silly. However, it is so because being wrong still feels so damn costly. We need to get over that online too - but online is just not the best way to do it, especially because of the LW people having such a strong, and often inconsiderate voice. I admire them but they are a mighty force on the internet, despite all being lovely people. They are so advanced with so many things and are not very welcoming to level other people up along the lines, there's a lot of in-groupy shit going on and the EA meme group (currently Jeff Jordan has Donkey Brains, before OMfCT) is a light, even worse version of this.

ea_welcoming_comment:
- Very welcoming in some ways—polite, measured, slow to run off an angry Facebook criticism, etc.
- Artificial-seeming in some ways ("take this Facebook survey on how we could be more welcoming!").
- The rationalist sub-community is rather unwelcoming to any hint of religiously motivated interest in effective charity.
insecurity_comment: I am committed to being charitable, and not being a moron about it, but identifying as "an EA" feels strange to me. I don't ever expect to feel as committed to the community as those that take on that first-person label. I use EA groups and organizations as valuable resources to help me make decisions. I may use GiveWell to inform how I give my money away, for example; but I do not think that transforms my identity into "being a GW" or anything.

ea_org_comment: I don't know how feasible this would be, but it would be great if GiveWell could estimate how the cost of saving a life-equivalent has been rising over time, and Project its future rise. That way, people with investment opportunities at various expected rates of return—or various levels of confidence in their own ability to better decide where to give their money in the future—would have a more concrete basis on which to decide between giving now and investing / giving later.

ea_org_comment: I know that 80,000 Hours is geared toward talented graduates, but high school age and younger readers who live in a google-it culture encounter the site while trying to figure out what to do with their lives. The site can elicit feelings of anxiety and depression for young people who desperately want to make a difference, but struggle with the bureaucratic and signaling-focused environment of academics and the corporate world.  There's a lot of "If you're really smart, have enough money, and try really hard for 4+ years, you might be lucky enough to get a job where you can spend some of your time doing research, outside of your other commitments." That is not effective life-living. What I see missing is good explanations of fields like economics and computer science that demonstrate their value to young people, and that point to ways individuals can pursue the EA applications of domain knowledge on their own. Mental health resources on the website might be helpful, too. A forum might serves this purpose as well.

ea_org_comment: My loyalty to AIDS Ride South Africa, Ltd. stems from the fact that all cyclists and volunteers donate their time. As a 501(c)3 non-profit organization, 100% of all donations goes to support the cyclists and the bikes we donate and the needs of the ride. No one is paid. This may seem like a small difference between those agencies that hire others. These paid agencies are larger and more powerful. It is ARSA's belief that we are a model for dealing with the HIV and AIDS pandemic throughout the world in economically challenged countries. ARSA fights new infections through education and awareness while promoting healthier lifestyles through cycling. ARSA also reaches remote communities where medical services are scarce or non-existent. HIV positive riders put a kinder face on those living with HIV and AIDS, reducing fear, ignorance and stigma. ARSA also reaches high school and college age students with our messages of safety, the age group most resistant to information. ARSA also empowers women by making sure they participate in the ride while teaching them to ride a bike and giving them one thus increasing their mobility. I am willing to work to make this world a safer place that works better for everyone but I am not about to line the pockets of those making a career out of helping others. My husband has a kidney transplant so funds are limited but my talent is not. I can create a brand ID, posters, t-shirts, raise funds and produce documentaries. If everyone on earth did at least one thing to contribute to the welfare of others, we would all be a lot better off. Effective altruism is only effective when it doesn't use up all the donations of those who contribute in hopes of saving lives. I hope you will consider AIDS Ride South Africa a worth cause to add to your list. Thank you.

is_ea_comment: I'm your "typical" EA. I used to subscribe to some form of virtue ethics. I switched to being more consequentialist. I started and run an EA group at a University. I'm a programmer interested in AI and machine learning and would like to both learn more about AI to help offset AI risk (however insignificantly) or assist in data-driven policy research while earning to give to donate to GiveWell and ACE recommended charities. I regularly post lengthy responses to EA critics online and am well aware of all the philosophical arguments against EA, having read many of the articles and even scholarly articles starting to be published on the movement. I find becoming EA similar to when I lost my Christian faith and became agnostic. Once agnostic, explaining away Christianity or countering any arguments made against agnosticism by Christians became far easier and took far fewer cognitive resources. EA is the same. EA I have found is far easier a position to defend cognitively than any other moral stance or worldview I have to date taken. It takes bare minimal effort to make a solid argument for it and makes me incredible comfortable as a result I'm doing the right thing for the world. No other worldview has afforded me the luxury of such surety. Also, about 2/3 of my diet is Soylent and I have at least 2 EA shirts, and hardcopies of virtually every major EA book and many others from the "EA reading list" as audiobooks. I'm white and cis-gendared and probably come across as "weird" to many people, but in a charming way. Yea, I am pretty sure I fit the bill as the walking stereotype for EA.

ea_org_comment:
I remain skeptical of existential risk causes given my epicurean/time-relative interest account leanings with regards to population ethics. Death or the creation of life are both not inherently good/bad. If humanity is wiped out and it isn't that painful or doesn't disrupt human welfare much, I immediately don't see a problem. I don't find the "think of the human lives that could have otherwise experienced pleasure" that compelling given that microbes at the bottom of Antarctica (or any other number of organisms including machines) would likely survive human annihilation and would go on to have their own valid pleasures. I would simply think of such bacteria or machines as humanity's "children."

e.g. I'm far far more concerned with AI's societal level concerns such as mass unemployment. This isn't an immediate existential risk however. We survived the 1940s without going extinct as a species and would survive another as a species even if society as a whole crumbles. As far as AI in EA goes, I wish the non-existential risks of AI was emphasized more. AI risk and AI existential risk are two different things. If you had "AI Risk (excluding existential risk)" as one of the cause areas earlier in the survey I would have put is as being as important as cause prioritization.

Either way, I actually suspect my views on this will change. We shall see.

ea_org_comment:
Animal charity evaluator - 

re word why other charities aren't involved or evaluated.  Make the wording less negative so it doesn't look like you are picking on other charities for not being the most effective. I find such negativity to people helping and people being told they aren't doing a good enough job etc decreases morale. I've seen in activism people leave because of the negativity of the situation they are fighting for combined with the fighting about tactics and feeling like not having an impact etc. I just think if the explanations are more positively focused people will be happier and continue to help. Also an acknowledge that other issues are important too due to suffering involved but because the reason EA is important is because it has the biggest impact of reducing suffering. So instead of wording things like you're putting other charities down, recognise their effort and that their issue is important and then positively explain that EA strategies are what you advocate because it reduces a larger amount of suffering. I just don't want to see people who are passionate about a particular cause to feel they are being put down for their efforts.

I also think that, in line with 80K's increasing recognition of the paramount importance of personal fit, we shouldn't look down on people who allow emotional factors to enter into (e.g.) cause selection. Altruism is an emotionally-powered phenomenon for most people, so let's not undermine the very engine that powers its spread.

ea_org_comment: I find it hard to work up much concern about most kinds of existential risk because I am not sure whether human extinction would be a good or bad thing. There are good aspects to human existence (a lot of happiness is experienced by humans) but also bad aspects (a lot of suffering is experienced by humans, and probably much more is inflicted by humans on other beings). It's not at all clear to me whether the bad aspects outweigh the good aspects or vice versa, or how likely that is to change in the future, so I do not know whether human extinction is something I should work to facilitate or work to prevent.

insecurity_comment: From (admittedly little) reading I formed impression that EA aims to maximise sum of human welfare, whereas I would broaden to animals and biodiversity, and I favour metric to reduce human suffering, avoiding possibility that EA would increase human population and so in long-term cause reduced welfare.
ea_org_comment: I believe a priority is encouraging lower birth rates to increase per-person wealth, and allow space for wild animals and biodiversity. My impression, I may be wrong, is that Effective Altruism metrics focus on maximising the sum of welfare rather than average per-person welfare, and so might favour human population increase. Also I am concerned that wildlife population sizes have decreased over the last century and I am unsure how EA metrics handle that? I recognise that EA does feature individual animal welfare but that is not the same as a species' prosperity e.g. numbers, distribution range, genetic diversity, and average health.

ea_org_comment:
Challenge:

Becoming/remaining too limited to a small sub-section of the population. The whole movement is mostly focused on appealing to students and graduates at top universities, and there seems to be very little work done to spread the word to the population more widely (and I currently work with SHIC).
The longer this goes on, the worse the problem is likely to become. I am especially concerned by the idea of targeting groups who are statistically more likely to take up EA ideas through targeted marketing; this is likely to worsen the problem.
I realise that targeting these sorts of people is more efficient in the short-term, I just think it poses long-term dangers to the movement, especially in terms of making these ideas part of the political mainstream, rather than a body of academic/elite ideas.

Suggestions:

1) More SIMPLIFIED self-explanatory outreach (I am currently working on developing a curriculum to be used in secondary schools which introduce EA ideas to the sorts of work most school children will be doing in form-time / PHSE lessons anyway).
 
2) Leafleting? (I realise the effectiveness of this is not yet fully understood, due to conflicting studies and very hard-to-measure results, but I would recommend anyway for the reasons given previously)

ea_org_comment:
EA is the "ideology" (for lack of a better term) I identify the most with.

And yet I feel there is so little I can do to be a part of it.

I guess this is because I found out about it too late, when my main career choices had already been made.

I have decent and stable job at the government, mostly related to capital market regulation and law enforcement. Transitioning to another career at this point would be unwise and unrealistic as my skills are not transferable and I have people that depend on me financially.

While my current job does allow me to accomplish good things for society, it is hardly comparable to work in EA related causes and doesn't that much potential for earning to give either.

If the movement is to continue growing, it won't be able to rely so much on young people starting their careers. I hope someone will figure out a way to make better use of people like me.

first_heard_ea_comment: I was frustrated about the lack of information regarding how to maximize the good brought by donating one's monetary assets. As a result of searching online, I stumbled on GiveWell and then 80,000 Hours; back in 2010-2011 they were not nearly as far as these days, so I started thinking about the subject independently. While I was somewhat interested in EA during 2011-2016, it wasn't until 2017 when I started becoming more active about understanding the movement.
attend_local_group_comment: I don't think there are any local groups here. Based on my image of them, the most likely scenario is that I would attend twice and then decide that it's a waste of time for me when compared to getting more people into EA or being active on the EA Forum. That would depend on the people and activities, of course.
would_like_more_involvement: I'd like to learn more first
plan_donate_how_much: Roughly 85-90% of lifetime income, as either monetary assets or work resources depending on career path.
ea_career_comment: My career path was primarily influenced by my personal values which overlap a lot with the values of the EA movement. However, when deciding my career path those values were not influenced by the EA community.
improve_survey_comment:
I think there could be even more open-ended questions. Maybe.

Perhaps getting more details about peoples' career plans w.r.t. EA could be relevant. Especially if a majority of the respondents are not directly involved with the EA organizations.

This question should be the last thing in the survey.

The question regarding the compellingness of an argument for EA is ambiguous about whether it asks about how compelling is it for me, or how compelling do I think it is for the general public. Personally I think that both should be asked about. The argument is very compelling for me, but I don't think it would bring many new people to EA.

I would enjoy analysing the compellingness of multiple such arguments, rather than just one. In my opinion, there should be a box for open-ended comments attached to the question as well.
moral_philosophy: No opinion, or not familiar with these terms
ea_welcoming_comment:
I consider the community to be very welcoming towards new people, but also very difficult to get into. It seems like the community has too limited resources on dealing with this and overall there is an expectation towards people "getting involved" by themselves.

As for people like myself with prior understanding of the rationale behind EA, the community feels unwelcoming. There is no single person who would have the answer to all the questions, and it feels like finding material on EA beyond the basics requires a lot of digging unless one is affiliated with an EA organization directly.
insecurity_comment: I don't align myself with the views of most people in the EA community, which might be perceived negatively. Thus, I wish to challenge the beliefs of people in the community and spark meaningful conversation, but this requires a time commitment that I am currently not able to make.
ea_org_comment: Thanks to all of you for the hard work. I hope to have the opportunity to discuss with as many of you in person as possible.

ea_org_comment:
In general, effective altruism as a movement needs to focus more on on the 'effective' part.  There is a great deal of altruism in the world that is not being used effectively.  

EA organizations should set the example in how resources can be effectively directed to making real change, rather than just making people feel better about themselves.

The most effective force for change is hope, and hope comes when people can see a future better than the present. The most effective form of altruism is the one that inspires other towards more effective altruism.

This is all to say that EA needs to be much more visible to seriously consider itself as effective.

ea_org_comment:
What I asked myself today is: why is the movement called "effective" Altruism and not "efficient"? By my general understanding of the words effectiveness is concerned with doing the right thing whereas efficient is concerned with doing a thing right. If one speaks of effective altruism it implies that the focus is on identifying the "right" causes, hence, it implies that there is a qualitative difference between things that exist. To now make an objective call about effectiveness one needs to define a way to measure that qualitative difference to make it measurable. This is difficult because as an altruist by definition you want to act in the best interest of all. If you take all literally it means every thing that has an interest that means at a minimum everything that is capable of communicating its interest. Now to produce any kind of meaningful calculus for the posed problem 
1) on a personal level: one would need to find a way to infer the wanted behavior of oneself against all other things. In case of conflicting interests one would need to somehow reach consensus by either shifting terms of the discussion or the scope of the enquiry. 
2) on a global level: find a way to define the term effective altruism conceptually/mathematically so that it can be applied realistically to help resolve conflicting interests. It needs to be accepted unequivocally because otherwise conflicts may persist.
So I posit that "effective" altruism basically equals "behavior that creates consensus among all things". Now this is somewhat poetic and sounds very nice but I think it is questionable if the thinking in terms of qualitative differences between things is an efficient way of enabling "effective" altruism to be actually practiced.
I think that to reach behavior that creates consensus among all things a paradox has to be overcome. One has to accept that every moment is unique, thus, all things are unique and, thus, all things are the same. We know from our own experience that we want this uniqueness to be recognized, we look for people who love us and see us for who we are. Thus, I would argue that to gain consensus among all things, recognizing the individuality of things without (or only minimal) qualitative judgement is a strong if not necessary strategy. Quantitative analysis (in terms of efficiency) on the other hand can be done objectively and fact based. It can be offered by science without any moral sentiment. Consequently, I posit that effective altruism should maybe start to focus on providing tools for efficient altruism.

ea_org_comment:
Expected value maximization is not justified by the law of large numbers, especially as it concerns tail risks, like existential and suffering risks. 

I suspect existential risks, especially from AI, receive too much support in EA. Perhaps most prominently, OPP granted $30 million to OpenAI for only 3 years "for general support" (http://www.openphilanthropy.org/focus/global-catastrophic-risks/potential-risks-advanced-artificial-intelligence/openai-general-support). How much research and how many researchers will this cover? $10 million is enough to pay 50 people $200,000 each. The article says "OpenAI initially approached Open Philanthropy about potential funding for safety research, and we responded with the proposal for this grant." Why didn't OPP just do this and give them less? Instead OPP is spending $10 million a year for three years so Holden can be an advocate in meetings, but we can't make any demands on how the money is actually used? What does he expect from his advocay? Sounds like a lot of money for very little concrete in return. 

I also see some EAs that seem to take for granted that AI will replace rather than simply assist politicians and solve most of our political problems. I suspect most people won't want to be governed by black boxes, and AI won't resolve fundamental political differences between people.

ea_org_comment:
Effective altruism argues that we should make decisions based on the known impacts of proven interventions, and take into account uncertainties regarding future risks. A rigorous approach to uncertainty is valuable, but I worry that it creates an overly mechanistic impression of the world. In particular, I worry that it limits our conceptions of what is possible.

Evolution has built a crazily complex biological world, but billions of years ago it would be hard to see how multi-cellular organisms could emerge, let alone thinking creatures such as ourselves. Likewise, the development of technology shows an incremental expansion into a search space that presents remarkable novelty.

As we try to be altruistic in an effective way, I think it is essential that we acknowledge our limited ability to predict the effects we might have. This might mean recognising the potential disasters of GMOs (as Nassim Taleb has discussed), for example, or the potential benefits of alternative social arrangements.

This entails a fuzzier, less quantifiable notion of uncertainty. As Stuart Kauffman has put it: "Not only do we not know what *will* happen, we often do not even know what *can* happen." This should be equally humbling, terrifying and inspiring for effective altruists.

Fostering beneficial outcomes in such a complex world is not straightforward, or guaranteed. But rather than recast the world as predictable, or lower our sights to simpler problems, I believe we should embrace the challenge and opportunity it presents.

What might this look like? First, it is a psychological challenge. Our natural response to uncertainty is to reduce it. Our natural approach to the world is to explain and control it. An alternative attitude of humility and epoche is possible, but needs to be consciously pursued: an exploratory mindset which acknowledges irreducible uncertainty.

Second, it is a social challenge. What do we expect from one another when we don’t know where things could lead? It is hard to recruit supporters to a common goal which is subject to radical change. It is hard to seek followers when you are plagued by doubts. We need to find ways of collaborating and enlisting support based on common values, so we can explore together.

Finally, it is a methodological challenge. There is no solution to the problem of complexity, but there are more and less effective ways of dealing with it. Complex systems can be modelled and investigated. Insights from entrepreneurship, biology and computer science can suggest ways of exploring complex search spaces. But such ideas have only recently started to be applied to areas of ethical importance.

I am proud to consider myself an effective altruist, or at least an aspiring one. I think we should be as vocal as possible in trying to expand the cause, even if we cannot specify the ultimate effect.

ea_org_comment: People feel called to donate to charities/causes that they connect to personally regardless of whether those charities are effective. Activists are less moved by "what works" - they act according to what they are individually willing to do for the cause. In the animal protection community we tend to shame each other for not supporting certain strategies or tactics. We need to find ways of understanding why certain people do, or do not do, what authorities tell us is effective.

ea_org_comment: I think that 80,000 Hours focuses almost entirely on people who are (or believe themselves to be) able to do anything.  There is little focus on people who lack either the ability or opportunity to choose among a plethora of high-performing careers.  This focus either excludes the vast majority of job seekers or assumes that they have abilities and opportunities that they don't have.  Perhaps all (potential) EAs fit this bill, but that in itself is a problem.  EA shouldn't be directed only at such people.  It should be directed to everyone or at least a representative cross-section of society.

first_heard_ea_comment:
Was recommended this text by a family member engaged in the movement: http://effective-altruism.com/ea/5e/efficient_charity_do_unto_others/

As a tree hugger it provoked me and I had it in the back of my mind for a while until I found myself convinced.

Started following an EA Facebook page.

Also met smart and NICE people that were interested in EA, which contributed a lot to me becoming engaged in the movement.
would_attend_local_group: I know that there is already and I do attend
attend_local_group_comment: Have been involved in starting two EA groups / organizations.
ea_welcoming_comment: I find the specific people I know welcoming, but I feel that I very strongly identify the EA community with ideals that I cannot live up to, and this is a problem for me. All the talk about intelligence, being smart and a rational individual is extremely hard for me to identify with and I often feel that I don't belong among EA people. I am not saying the community would be more successful without these strong ideals, I am only saying I would have done more good if not for them.

ea_org_comment:
One thing I wonder: can we really pick the most effective charities? I'm thinking say of the stock market, and how professional investors typically can't beat an index of stocks (eg S&P 500). This leads investors like me to have an index-based investment strategy.

I wonder if this kind of analysis has been done for non-profits. It's interesting, because if so, it would mean that we should probably adopt an approach of supporting a broad set of organizations rather than, say, directing every EA to donate all they can to the Against Malaria Foundation (for example).

Related to that, I wonder how the EA giving strategy would work out if everyone applied it. My concern is that we need a broad base of non-profits that are thriving in various parts of the world, and that if the focus was to fund one "big cause" at a time until the issue is solved, we might be worse off in the end than if we gave broad support to a large number of initiatives.

Mentioned above: I think EAs have wrongly neglected environmental questions. If you care about animal welfare, say, than the fact that current practices are leading to one of the largest ever extinction rates for non-human species seems to me to put this issue right at the top of  "cause prioritization" as a current, ongoing, massive existential risk. And yet the only EA recommendation I've seen on this front is William McAskill recommending a GHG offset non-profit. Full disclosure: I'm a very committed environmentalist.

first_heard_ea_comment:
I was introduced to 80,000 hours at freshers' fair at university but took a while to actually get involved with them. I think I was introduced to Giving What We Can around the same time, but I am not sure of the exact chronology.

PS 2014 is kind of an estimate- I first heard of 80,000 hours in 2013, and it was some time before I was introduced to "EA" and a bit longer before I got involved in any way...
attend_local_group_comment: I likely would not attend all the events unless I was helping organize them (e.g. in Oxford I attended a few events)
improve_survey_comment: Early in the survey you asked about the likelihood of recommending a friend to join the EA community. I am very likely to recommend the principles of EA to friends/family and to direct them to certain articles. However, I'm a little less likely to recommend the "community" to them, as there are some aspects of it that are pretty off-putting (e.g. certain talks available to watch as videos, overly utilitarian approach (beyond the maximizing effectiveness of helping charity, which is a much easier sell), sometimes seeming singleminded focus on a particular metric for a problem (e.g. years of healthy life saved when a child is saved from malaria) without considering other suffering (e.g. the parents' enormous sorrow at having their child die) and thus coming to some pretty repugnant conclusions, some people just being put off by the big words, inaccessible "business speak", and/or overly impersonal and mathsy approach to everything, the community being seemingly not that diverse, the inclusion of things like insect suffering on some lists of EA groups, etc). Anyway, separating out these things--recommending the community vs,=. explaining the concepts, recommending specific articles/events, etc. might get you a more accurate and helpful picture of people's attitudes (esp. if you ask the reasons why certain things might be less recommendable)

ea_welcoming_comment: Sure, the people are welcoming enough, but some of the extreme views and/or the general dry, impersonal, and sometimes hard to understand style of language can put people off
ea_org_comment: There is a danger of alienating people by including causes well outside the mainstream circle of empathy (e.g. insect suffering), especially when there are still children dying of malaria, being killed in wars, etc.). Cold attitudes and casually talking about how a child not dying harms the world for Neo-Malthusian overpopulation reasons (as at least one person from a EA conference available online does) is also off-putting.

ea_org_comment:
Effective altruism in general has satured its own brand and needs to become mainstream. The use of identity labeling (like "effective altruism") is useful for getting past the initial organization hump of critical mass, but thence the label must be shed or it will become too easy to target its suppression. All sufficiently successful EA's should be advised to permanently shed the EA label and focus their core defining label on another area: CEO of a large corporation, mayor or governor of a city or state, seminary entry to priesthood or clergy in a religious organization with access to many altruistic minds (if not sharing one's ontology). For the latter, note that (undercover atheist) deacons are allowed to participate in religious ceremonies and have access to thousands of members of a congregation, admitting to potentially refactorable tithing. If, for example, an EA landed the post of Catholic bishop, archbishop, or cardinal, some massive opportunities would become available to redirection of funds typically allocated by the Catholic Church to ineffective charities. Unfortunately, most EA's are unwilling to compartmentalize their identity and inflict ego death, thereby allowing themselves to carry logically incompatible labels and belief systems which hold much greater utility than sticking like a herd to a single targetable and neutralizable label (like "effective altruist"). The end result is that EA goals will be accomplished much slower than they could be.

Thus my recommendations to specific organizations are as follows:

Agnostic - Identify the political and religious affiliation breakdown of the organization--why does it not conform to the same histogram as that for all United States society? And why is that not considered a problem? If you can't pull in people to stabilize a distribution and make it conform to that of the United States (or the global community), self-modify to make yourself *fit* that distribution by incorporating into yourself belief systems that you do not a priori agree with. Everyone is, after all, human, and you should have the cognitive toolkit to understand and act isomorphically with that belief system indefinitely. (In the back of your mind, you can always whisper "I'm an EA!") The potential ramifications are massive: access to communities we are currently isolating ourselves from because we are getting branded, and branding is the first step to neutralization. 

Charity Science - Stop using the words "Charity" and "Science" in your project titles. Most people don't care about charity and even less people care about science. It evokes a fuzzy feeling to you, but names matter and I doubt these are the instrumentally most effective names for accomplishing the goals of the organization.

GiveWell - Great organization, not much commentary. I do take some notice of the recent LessWrong post about being careful to self-recommend EA funds and divest or at least weigh more heavily into external non-EA controlled non-profit funds.

GWWC - No major commentary.

80000 hours - Needs to emphasize reading things like Warren Buffet's Annual Letters to Shareholders, McKinsey's textbook on Valuations, and generally assuming the identity of business owner and equityholder rather than employee. The richest people are those who know how to harness exponential growth and take ownership over its future discounted cash flows. Stop looking for high-salary jobs.

MIRI - I like the new agenda that lies halfway between the OpenAI and Agent Foundations agenda on a logarithmic scale, as measured by mathematical formality. No major improvements to suggest at this moment -- Patrick, Jessica, Nate et al are doing a great job.

FHI, FRI - Haven't followed enough to comment on major suggestions.

ACE, Animal Protection - Seems like their recommendations are objective and fair. Really like the transparency. No major commentary.

Global poverty - Need to increase focus on this. Existential risk is incredibly important but also still far from saleable to the mainstream.

Existential risk - Obviously the most critical priority but unfortunately it is highly sub-optimal to advertise that publicly at the moment.

Finally, a resting thought: Friendly AI is a *means* to an *end*. Think about what *you* would be working on if you *were* the Friendly AI and then *go work on it*. Are you sure you don't have the requisite intelligence? Capital? Resources? Political maneuverability? Forget about plucking atoms into utopia with nanotechnology, just roll your sleeves up, step into the dirt, and use business, politics, and interaction with religious community to give what you can and accomplish the highest impact.

ea_welcoming_comment:
I find EA welcoming if you share their core values, but EA becomes much colder towards people with different values. 

More in detail: I think EAs are biased towards certain beliefs and it is hard to engage with them if you do not share them. While I do not expect EAs would welcome nazis, I expected it would be a bit more open towards people who are trying to be effective altruists (with lower case i.e. people who are genuinely concerned for others, and looking for the most effective ways to help them), but who do not share their biases in favour of the current causes chosen by EA meta-charities.

A positive comment: when I have approached EA to discuss my views, with one exception, the conversation reaches a point where the EA justifies themself saying "this is what actually, truly feels right", similarly to Yudkowsi in his Less Wrong morality and meta-morality posts

ea_org_comment:
First, a technical point. As I have insisted before: I do not understand why EA uses such an unscientific method for exploring conceptual landscapes such as "brainstorming" and "talking to people". Why not use a more systematic approach, such as trying to define more or less formally the total space of possibilities, and then exploring it systematically?

Another comment: when I have approached EAs to discuss differences in our views (this has happened 8-10 times, with very involved EAs), every single time except one (where the person I was speaking with did not really understand what I was saying, and dropped the conversation), the conversation reaches a point where the EA justifies themself saying something along the lines of "yeah, well, this is what ultimately, truly feels right, and it is consistent with everything else we know, and most people care about", which not too surprising, given that this is similar to Yudkowsi's answer in his Less Wrong morality and meta-morality posts, or to what I myself would say, pressed with the same questions.

But the disagreement comes in what particular things we feel have value. Currently, EAs view of value is not very aligned with mine, so I  pursue my research for the most effective ways of doing good outside EA. Nevertheless I try to keep in touch to see if either I change my mind, or EA shifts closer to my views.

ea_org_comment:
Copied from my answer about neglected areas, since it sounds like this comment box goes to a different audience: Combating religion seems huge to me. A large part of most people's lack of rationality stems from a culture in which accepting things on faith from authoritative figures is baked into our intellectual development from a very early age. Critical thinking is suppressed by very early religious indoctrination, and this is extremely troubling but I don't see much attention for this issue in EA circles. Perhaps I am just not aware of this part of the movement as most of my awareness revolves around animal welfare and global development. 

Another concern I have about the movement is the propensity to prioritize easily measurable impacts simply because they give a nice, quantifiable metric. A lot of the causes we work towards are large, complex, and slow-moving, and our impact on moving the needle is often indirect. In many cases we are talking about cultural shifts in attitude, where planting a seed in one's mind may not pay dividends until months or years later, beyond the typical timescale of assessment follow-up. In fact, the individual affected by the work may not even, at the time their behavior finally changes, even be able to recall where the initial impetus came from. But this is not to say that that work is not valuable; we simply don't have a means of measuring it.

Perhaps more harmful than prioritizing measurable activities over non-measurable influence is the tendency to try to quantify impact but going about it in a flawed manner. The results not only most likely don't reflect reality, but they give the false sense of security that they do - and thus more resources are confidently poured into one direction or another based on that information, when in reality a more balanced approach should be taken if the study is too flawed to give accurate prescriptive information. I have seen this quite a bit. In my opinion, performing a severely biased and not statistically valid study to assess efficacy is worse than performing no such study because of the false assurance it provides.

ea_org_comment:
EA is a fascinating phenomenon, with the potential for bringing about huge progress on the world's most important issues. I am in awe of our commitment to act as well as discuss, our high level of discussion, our responsiveness to criticism, and general sincerity. I've spent a lot of the past year volunteering for an EA organisation, and aim to dedicate my life to promoting effective systemic change as a direct result of this.

EA is still a very small social movement, but has the huge potential. But rich white rationalists cannot achieve this potential without large-scale engagement with other groups. we must get serious about addressing our lack of diversity, get serious about routes into systemic change, and expand our rhetoric to appeal to non-rationalists. We must speak the language of injustice, and attract all who seek to fight it effectively - this is far from the case yet.

ea_org_comment: I believe that a lack of influence, funding out of the box approaches, and strategic thinking is seriously impacting the EA movement. If the EA movement had access to massive political and economic influence (e.g. if it was Google and had influence over governments) there is a far greater chance its goals would be achieved. If it explored sustainable solutions like social enterprises instead of cash transfers, there is the chance such a solution could be scalable and influence-building. I also think there is a lack of support for new EA projects, nonprofits, and charities. I believe x-risk and managing the technological, societal, and cultural changes that will come from technological advances is a significant area of concern, more so than donating bednets and such. Approaches like reforming existing charitable solutions, rather than direct donations, are more likely to have a sizably larger impact.

ea_org_comment:
I appreciate a secular agenda, but the proverbial elephant in the room is the impact religion has on society for bad and good. Individual rights have been restricted by narrow-minded religious people and horrific abuses made by terrorists claiming to be religious. At the same time, hospitals, orphanages, nursing homes, schools, and many other social institutions have been founded and ran by religious people. EA may wisely tread lightly, so as not to over-step in defining good versus bad spirituality. But it may at least benefit from addressing the extremes by pointing out what gives or destroys life. Likewise for the virtues or vices that makes wise, heroic leaders versus those who lead others astray.

If religiosity seems to be on decline, at least in the West, I'd suggest another matter is bringing increasing impact: electronics. Especially when combined with media, it acts as a magnifier. Pornography is amplified as an all-consuming addiction, made even more immersive by virtual reality, but virtual reality can also teach empathy and compassion. Without mindfulness, online activities can increase a person's superficiality and impulsiveness, while groups like EA can use the Internet to make good connections, teach and inspire.

Then, you mix these areas, and you often get a sequence that be complex in its impact. For example, Arab Spring freed a multitude from oppressive dictators but it also left a void that was filled by ISIS and al Qaeda. The dynamics of altruism can have similar far-reaching effects.

ea_org_comment:
I really love the EA philosophy and volunteer putting together events at my local club. I wince at calling it a "movement" because I think there are many, many organizations that strive to be "effective" and so this turns a lot of people away from the ideas. It can be challenging to explain EA to other people, aside from asking them to read a webpage.

I think what is happening in the political United States is putting a dent in the ability of EA to grow. There seems to be more urgent issues at home, even if third world development issues are "more important". It's hard on "recruitment" but also in self-assurance.

Sometimes I think that the EA community doesn't consider women equal, or consider women's issues or family planning as topics worth considering. I'd really like to see this develop.

ea_org_comment: I'm not good with money stuff, but here's an idea that I had: start a US student loan fund in which immediate payoff of loans is provided in exchange for x years of effective donations (some % of income). Have some of the donated money feed back into the fund to sustain itself. Testing would have to be done to see if this would only be a good idea for people above a certain earning potential threshold. ea_career_comment: I think it's important to distinguish the movement from the philosophy. So I believe in EA and find the resources very useful but I don't think I could say the research alone changed my career path, it factored in alongside lots of other influences.
improve_survey_comment: So I primarily interact with 80,000 Hours not the Centre for E.A. and sometimes it wasn't clear what you were referring to. There were also a lot of questions to get more involved with the community - fine - whereas I was expecting to contribute to research - so either adjust the survey or manage expectations better. Also I feel for me effective altruism as a philosophy is very important but the movement is not a regular feature of my life - neither do I feel it has scope to beyond being a useful resource - because there are other groups that are more useful for me pursuing EA within my field.
ea_welcoming_comment: This seems quite cultish. I.e., I think we have a shared belief that it's important to think through actions for their positive benefit but I don't think that warrants a separation vs. the rest of people.
ea_org_comment:
For reaching beyond academia, it may be worth to simplify a lot of the language. I like how you create different products - e.g., 80,000 Hrs fulfils a clear purpose

The other big blind spot is that there are lots of charities that are potentially very cost-effective/high-impact that you don't list because they're not engaging in your process. This means you prioritise smaller charities, ran by people like you, that deliver relatively simple easy-to-explain and easy-to-evaluate interventions

first_heard_ea_comment: As noted above I have been aware of / implementing EA for the past 20 years starting from my mid twenties. I started as soon as I had an income beyond my living expenses.  When I became a director of an aid organisation in 2000 I aimed to have some meta influence through the content of newsletters, other publications and radio and tv advertising. I have my own donor directed charitable trust fund into which I put money, as well as donating directly to other charities.  I volunteer on phones at a suicide/crisis hotline and have probably saved a few lives that way e.g. by relieving distress or suicidal thoughts, or helping organise an emergency response.
attend_local_group_comment: Might be prepared to start one in my area in which case I'd take the pledge.
plan_donate_how_much: I am weighing up various investment and financial options but am likely to consistently donate about 8-10% based on my current income.
ea_career_comment: EA factors have had an impact on my overall life career, but I didn't have any good reasons for "choosing" my legal career which I hate and do merely as a default option, I should have stuck to professional tennis which I tried after leaving school, or done medicine or psychology, or just about anything else instead.  I'd be far more able to donate money know if I had just got any job after leaving school and focussed on property investing, instead of wasting years at university which was demoralising and which did not lead to a proportionate increase in income from personal exertion.
improve_survey_comment: The survey is very narrow, it focusses on the amount of money donated, but not, for example, on amount of money raised, and or amount of any direct influence on others to give.  It also doesn't focus much on voluntary work, e.g. I regard my work at a suicide/crisis hotline as an important component of my altruistic endeavour. Nor does it ask about overall way of life, e.g. given the millions of people killed by alcohol every year world wide I think it is unethical to contribute to the profit of the alcohol industry by using alcohol. The survey also doesn't ask about other types of donation, e.g. blood donation.
moral_philosophy: No opinion, or not familiar with these terms
ea_welcoming_comment: Haven't really pursued it so far but the newsletters have been good.
insecurity_comment: Not really, but it's been a minor factor given my income is larger than average but in 2015 and 2016 I couldn't donate much due to some difficult family law issues.

ea_org_comment:
No comments beyond those above, except I have selected short term causes below because some of them are very urgent and unless they are addressed the long term issues will become irrelevant because such major impacts will have already occurred. And clearly, for the world's poorest people impacts such as death are already happening.   

I have now just seen the next question about an argument for donating a substantial amount of money / income to effective charities being that beyond a certain amount of income more income does not make much difference to our wellbeing.  

I find one aspect of this argument to be VERY WEAK, because for me having a lot more money would make a VERY MAJOR difference to my wellbeing because I could then more easily avoid my day job as a lawyer which I loathe, have more time to help others / look after my son etc, be more able to afford a safer motor vehicle or house, be more able to pay for medical treatment for me or my family or friends if needed. Further, if I didn't need to work to be able to live in my current house I would have no trouble in filling my time with interesting and enjoyable activities that would give me vastly more enjoyment than my day job.  

I also find it a bit annoying that it is assumed that the reader will be just like whoever the people are that the argument is based on.

This aspect is a real turn off for me, and I donate despite, not because of it. 

The aspect about happiness from material things being about comparative issues is also weak and a turn off for me.  It is weak because the REALITY is that if people have a lot less than their friends and family they may feel they have failed (whether rightly or wrongly) and this will impact on their happiness unless they manage to modify their thinking which they may be unable to do. 

I think it is clearly wrong and misleading to assert that "the personal costs of donating a substantial amount of money are likely small". They may be small, or they may be large.  It depends on individual circumstances. 

If donating a lot of money early in your life means that you miss out on investment opportunities and miss out on the chance to retire early and are stuck in a job you hate and get health and / or relationship problems as a result of working overtime in the crappy job then obviously the personal cost of donating may be very major indeed.  

That is not a reason not to donate of course and I am certainly not advocating that people donate nothing while young and invest every dollar in property or shares, but I think some more nuanced arguments are needed, or at least ones which are not demonstrably false.     

The aspect about donating leading to satisfaction is much better.  That aspect should be emphasised more and expanded in my view.

ea_org_comment:
I worry that EA may overly emphasize animal welfare, but it is a difficult claim to make without a more fleshed out view of animal ethics than I am currently willing to commit to. 

I also worry that EA is diversifying too much: in theory, one cause area must have the highest expected value. Hedging your bets is not a way to maximize expected outcomes, so by maintaining prioritization of global poverty, AI, the environment, animal welfare, other ex-risks,  and more, we may be failing to devote enough attention and resources to whichever is actually the single highest expected value. Of course, you want to maintain some diversification for the ability to identify higher expected value areas in the future, but it is a trade-off that we may not be making appropriately in my opinion. Particularly if we actually believe that AI is tractable, it seems unclear why any other cause areas would be worth prioritizing when we may be able to solve them all simultaneously with friendly AI (I realize that this makes it sound far more simple than it is, but at the end of the day that statement may be true). 

As mentioned before, I worry about what direction the people in the inner circles of EA will choose to take the movement in, but not actually being involved in those inner circles I don't feel qualified enough or justified to critique in greater depth since I don't know what goes into each decision. 

It's hard to make a cohesive movement out of a group of people who pride themselves on and continually strive to be unique leaders and critical observers, not accepting followers.

ea_career_comment: I am moving away from combat arms and have found interest in pursuing a career in operations research.  This will allow me to do a lot of good not only in the military but in the private and non-profit sector as well.
ea_org_comment:
Perhaps more reminders about what is actually at stake (trillions of life forms with intense levels of well-being) and the efficacy of action would be useful.  People forget, or aren't even aware of what is truly at stake, and people do not realize how much good they can actually do.

Also, this may not be the best universal philosophy, but I am sympathetic to preventing years of suffering and promoting years of well-being that wouldn't happen otherwise.  Forgive me, but when I hear about a life being saved, especially a life in a developing country full of suffering, I am not moved to action as much as if someone describes how this person's wellbeing will be improved and how their life will become well worth living through my donations.

In essence, I don't care about saving lives, I care about well-being and making lives worth living. There is no sense in saving a life it will not be worth living.  I know many EA charities do wonders for well-being, so I donate to EA charities.  However, perhaps not everyone realizes that, and EA charities would be able to capture more of their audience if they marketed more to people with this belief.

first_heard_ea_comment:
Well, I am a Christian, and Jesus taught me that I had a duty to be altruistic. Or more accurately, His parables expertly called my attention to a duty that my God-given conscience recognized to be genuine (and this is one of the reasons I see Him as being genuine too). Next step on the journey is developing a genuine love out of which altruism just flows easily without being prodded by duty, but I'm not quite there yet.

As for the effective part, I think that's somewhat self-evident, even if it's not widely done at a high level.  I work in hedge fund management and using quantitative methods to measure effectiveness is an everyday affair, so I was pleased to find GiveWell a few years ago, the best resource I've ever found for this kind of research.

But I was a believer in EA long before I knew about that particular label for it.

improve_survey_comment:
I am a librarian for Oxford University. I have no idea how to answer your profession questions - is Oxford a 'non-profit'? I suppose so, it's a charity. It's also partly publicly-funded and comes under Freedom of Informatio - does that make it a Government org? I am not an academic, I am technically a member of administrative + support staff.

There should a higher education (or education!) option under field of work or study.

ea_org_comment:
I love the practicality of Giving What We Can - just sign up, sort it out, don't need to think about it again. I've always had good experiences dealing with their staff when I've had queries.

I'm just not that interested in ex-risk and I feel a bit like I'm going to be judged and asked to justify that if I spend more time in the EA community.

I think EA somehow isolates itself from other philanthropists and groups of them by appearing holier than thou. This seems like such a shame and detriment to our group - these people are on our side!!

I find the idea of networking in any context absolutely abhorrent and terrifying, so it is really, really difficult for me to motivate myself to go to EA Global (I am planning to do so this year!) or most social meetups as they seem a bit too corporate and intense for me. As an example, I went to EAGx in Oxford a few years ago and one session started with 'let's do a mini-networking game to get to know one another' and I simply walked out and got a cup of coffee and came back later. I think there is a feeling that if you *really cared* you'd magically be able to enjoy and do all things like that, or like organising a team or running a fundraiser or convincing all your friends to become EAs. But people have different talents and the community should learn how to harness them individually and not force people into moulds they don't fit.
